{"title_page": "Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Zuloaga MNCARS.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Pl\u00e1cido painted by his son, [[Ignacio Zuloaga]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1834|10|05}}\n| birth_place      = [[Madrid]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1910|07|01|1834|10|05}} \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Spanish\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = [[damascening]]\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = [[Eibar]], Spain\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = Luc\u00eda Zamora y Zabaleta, Francisca Gil y Lete\n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Pl\u00e1cido Maria Martin Zuloaga y Zuloaga'''{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=42}} (5 October 1834\u20131 July 1910),<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://dbe.rah.es/biografias/119248/placido-zuloaga-y-zuloaga|title=Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga y Zuloaga {{!}} Real Academia de la Historia|website=dbe.rah.es|access-date=2020-04-09|language=Spanish}}</ref> was a Spanish [[Sculpture|sculptor]] and [[Metalworking|metalworker]]. He is known for perfecting [[damascening]], a metalwork technique that involves inlaying gold, silver and other metals into a metal surface, creating an intricate decorative effect. He exhibited his art works at [[World's fair|international fairs]] and was recognised with multiple awards. Zuloaga came from a family of [[Basques|Basque]] metalworkers. He was the son of damascening pioneer [[Eusebio Zuloaga]], the half-brother of the painter and ceramic artist [[Daniel Zuloaga]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and the father of the painter [[Ignacio Zuloaga]]. He improved on the techniques introduced by his father, perfecting a process for inlaying gold and silver into iron.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=37}}\n\n== Early life ==\nPl\u00e1cido was born in 1834 in [[Madrid]] to Eusebio and Antonia Zuloaga. His father was the director of the [[Royal Armoury of Madrid|Spanish Royal Armoury]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The Zuloaga family were based in Eibar and producing armaments as far back as 1596.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|41}} Pl\u00e1cido learned in his father's workshop from an early age.<ref name=\":0\" /> At fourteen, he visited [[Paris]] where he learned from the armourer [[Faur\u00e9 Le Page|Lepage]]. In [[Dresden]], he studied under [[Antoine-Louis Barye]] and [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1867 his father let him take over administration of the family factory in [[Eibar]].<ref name=\":0\" /> It is thought that he had already been carrying out his father's commissions for a decade at this point.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=43}} Once in charge of the workshop, he employed and trained many craftsmen in damascening, directing the factory's production away from armanents and towards making art works.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\nMany of Zuloaga's works are so intricate they could not feasibly be made by one person; he led a team of specialist artisans who carried out his designs.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} Damascening involves indenting the iron surface, then pressing fine gold wire and heating the surface so that the gold forms a solid shape.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=45}} Whereas modern damascening uses acid etching to create the indentations, Zuloaga and his workshop did so with hand tools.<ref>Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro \"Damascene as part of the Engraver's Art\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 37</ref> Zuloaga worked when gold was relatively abundant and his works make greater use of it than later Spanish damascene.<ref>Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro \"Damascene as part of the Engraver's Art\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 38</ref> Although he made objects with a practical use, they are so delicate they would be damaged by ordinary use. Zuloaga's goal was beauty rather than practical utility.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}}\n\nMore than a hundred pieces of Spanish damascened metalwork, including 22 signed by Zuolaga, have been collected by the British-Iranian scholar and philanthropist [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]], forming one of [[Khalili Collections|his eight collections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/spanish-damascene-metalwork/|title=Spanish Damascene Metalwork|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Included in these are the Fonthill Casket, a {{convert|201|cm|in}} wide iron [[cassone]] with gold and silver damascening, decorated inside with white enamel with black ornamentation inside and out. Commissioned by the English collector [[Alfred Morrison]], it acquired its name from Fonthill manor, Morrison's family home. Zuloaga and his specialists took took two years to construct the casket,{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=71}} which was described in 1879 as \"a triumph of skilled workmanship\".{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}} Also commissioned by Morrison are a pair of [[amphora]]-shaped urns, {{convert|108|cm|in}} high, from 1878 whose style imitated the medieval [[Hispano-Moresque ware|Alhambra vases]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=83}} Covered in intricate Hispano-Arabic decoration, possibly drawn from contemporary engravings of a specific Alhambra vase, these were exhibited in Paris before delivery to Morrison.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=83}}\n\nA writing desk dated 1884\u20131885 has 44 drawers in a wooden case, each with enamelled floral patterns and a damascened metal button-pull.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=108}} Not a woodworker himself, Zuloaga would have subcontracted out the preparation of the wood and veneer.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=108}} A {{convert|47.3|cm|in}} high iron shrine dated 1880 recalls [[Gothic architecture]] in its overall shape, but the intricate damascened decoration is more suggestive of [[art nouveau]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=104}} It contains a cast silver figure of the Virgin and Child in a gothic style.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=104}} Other objects signed by Zuloaga include a [[revolver]],{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=102}} [[Decorative box|snuff boxes]] and caskets and containers of various dimensions.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|pp=90\u2013114}}\n\nAround 1872, Zuloaga's workshop was commissioned to make the monumental [[sarcophagus]] for [[Juan Prim, 1st Count of Reus|General Juan Prim]]. Work began in Eibar, but due to the [[Third Carlist War|civil war of 1873]] he moved his workshop across to the border to [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] in France where the work was completed. Prim's tomb now resides in the cemetary at [[Reus]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=58}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascene Metalwork cassone, Elbar.jpg|The Fonthill Casket: forged iron [[cassone]], 1871\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL104.jpg|Pair of iron urns, before 1878\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL105.jpg|Writing or document desk, 1884-1885\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL095.jpg|Iron shrine with [[Madonna (art)|virgin and child]], unknown date\n</gallery>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWith his first wife Luc\u00eda Zamora y Zabaleta, he had ten children, five of whom survived to adulthood, including [[Ignacio Zuloaga]] who would become a noted painter. After Lucia died, he married Francisca Gil y Lete.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Recognition and legacy ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL108.jpg|thumb|right|Iron table clock, circa 1880]]\nZuloaga died in Madrid at the age of 76 on 10 July 1910 and is interred in the cemetery at [[Canillejas]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} Several of his trainees continued as noted artists in their own right and EIbar continued as the centre of Spanish damascene production until the [[Spanish Civil War]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}}\n\nDuring his life, Zuolaga was awarded the Officer of the [[Legion of Honour|French Legion of Honor]], Knight Commander of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic|Order of Isabel the Catholic]], Knight of the Great Cross of Charles III, Knight of the Great Cross of the Lion and Sword of Sweden, Cross of King Leopold of Belgium, Knight of the Portuguese Order of St. James, Grand Cross of Santiago of Portugal, and Knight of the Order of Maria Teresa of Austria.<ref name=\":0\" />{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} He won many gold and silver medals at national and international exhibitions.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}}\n\nThe critical reception of Zuloaga's art, and of Spanish damascened metalwork generally, has changed greatly over time. In 1872, the Keeper of Art Collections in the South Kensington Museum (later renamed the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]]) wrote that a [[L\u00e9onard Morel-Ladeuil]] vase decorated by Zuloaga \"will be regarded as one of the greatest Art productions of the century\".<ref name=\"blair\" /> An 1879 article said that the his works showed a patience and effort that \"take one into an era when the fine arts producer devoted himself solely to the cause of his ''m\u00e9tier'', apart from the commercial considerations of time, trouble and expense.\"{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}} Early twentieth-century art critics took a more negative view of the Zuloaga family's works, but a new wave of interest and critical appreciation emerged in the last decades of that century.<ref name=\"blair\">[[Claude Blair|Blair, Claude]] \"Introduction\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 9</ref> Nasser Khalili, who writes that \"Spain [has] always led the West in its beauty and quality of its damascene production\", describes Zuloaga as \"the supreme damascener of [his] family\".<ref>[[Nasser Khalili|Khalili, Nasser D.]] \"Foreword\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 8</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork zul109.jpg|thumb|right|Bronze gilt and enamelled casket, unknown date]]\nZuloaga exhibited his works at the 1855 [[Exposition Universelle (1855)|Paris International Exposition]] (where he was awarded a Medal of Honour)<ref name=\":0\" /> and at the Madrid Exhibition and the Brussels International Exhibition of 1856, then at the [[1862 International Exhibition|Great London Exposition]] of 1862.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMore recently, the following exhibitions have featured his work:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/the-eight-collections-2/|title=The Eight Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=nasserdkhalili.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Spanish Treasures from The Khalili Collection''\n\n* May 1997 \u2013 Jan 1998 [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], London, UK\n\n''El Arte y Tradici\u00f3n de los Zuloaga: Damasquinado Espa\u00f1ol de la Colecci\u00f3n Khalili''\n\n* May \u2013 Aug 2000 [[Museo de Bellas Artes de Bilbao|Museo de Bellas Artes]], Bilbao, Spain\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2001 [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]], Granada, Spain\n* May \u2013 Sep 2001 [[Real Fundacion de Toledo]], Toledo, Spain\n\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Meisterwerke in gold, silber und eisen damaszener\u2013schmiedekunst aus der Khalili-Sammlung''\n\n* Apr \u2013 Aug 2003 [[Roemer- und Pelizaeus-Museum Hildesheim|Roemer und Pelizaeus Museum]], Hildesheim, Germany\n\n''Metal Magic: Spanish Treasures from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Nov 2011 \u2013 Apr 2012 [[Auberge de Provence]], Valletta, Malta\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Commons cat|Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Lavin|first=James D.|url=|title=The art and tradition of the Zuloagas : Spanish damascene from the Khalili Collection|date=1997|publisher=Khalili Family Trust in association with the Victoria and Albert Museum|others=|year=|isbn=1-874780-10-2|location=Oxford|pages=|oclc=37560664|ref=harv}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuloaga, Pl\u00e1cido}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:19th-century Spanish artists\u200e]]\n[[Category:People from Eibar]]\n[[Category:Spanish male artists]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:19th-century male artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish metalsmiths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Zuloaga MNCARS.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = Pl\u00e1cido painted by his son, [[Ignacio Zuloaga]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1834|10|05}}\n| birth_place      = [[Madrid]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1910|07|01|1834|10|05}} \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = Spanish\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = [[damascening]]\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = [[Eibar]], Spain\n| movement         = \n| spouse           = Luc\u00eda Zamora y Zabaleta, Francisca Gil y Lete\n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| module           = \n}}\n'''Pl\u00e1cido Maria Martin Zuloaga y Zuloaga'''{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=42}} (5 October 1834\u20131 July 1910),<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://dbe.rah.es/biografias/119248/placido-zuloaga-y-zuloaga|title=Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga y Zuloaga {{!}} Real Academia de la Historia|website=dbe.rah.es|access-date=2020-04-09|language=Spanish}}</ref> was a Spanish [[Sculpture|sculptor]] and [[Metalworking|metalworker]]. He is known for perfecting [[damascening]], a metalwork technique that involves inlaying gold, silver and other metals into a metal surface, creating an intricate decorative effect. He exhibited his art works at [[World's fair|international fairs]] and was recognised with multiple awards. Zuloaga came from a family of [[Basques|Basque]] metalworkers. He was the son of damascening pioneer [[Eusebio Zuloaga]], the half-brother of the painter and ceramic artist [[Daniel Zuloaga]],<ref name=\":0\" /> and the father of the painter [[Ignacio Zuloaga]]. He improved on the techniques introduced by his father, perfecting a process for inlaying gold and silver into iron.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=37}}\n\n== Early life ==\n\nPl\u00e1cido was born in 1834 in [[Madrid]] to Eusebio and Antonia Zuloaga. His father was the director of the [[Royal Armoury of Madrid|Spanish Royal Armoury]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Pl\u00e1cido learned in his father's workshop from an early age.<ref name=\":0\" /> At fourteen, he visited [[Paris]] where he learned from the armourer [[Faur\u00e9 Le Page|Lepage]]. In [[Dresden]], he studied under [[Antoine-Louis Barye]] and [[Jean-Baptiste Carpeaux]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1867 his father let him take over administration of the family factory in [[Eibar]].<ref name=\":0\" /> It is thought that he had already been carrying out his father's commissions for a decade at this point.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=43}} Once in charge of the workshop, he employed and trained many craftsmen in damascening, directing the factory's production away from armanents and towards making art works.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Works ==\nMany of Zuloaga's works are so intricate they could not feasibly be made by one person; he led a team of specialist artisans who carried out his designs.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} Damascening involves indenting the iron surface, then pressing fine gold wire and heating the surface so that the gold forms a solid shape.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=45}} Whereas modern damascening uses acid etching to create the indentations, Zuloaga and his workshop did so with hand tools.<ref>Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro \"Damascene as part of the Engraver's Art\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 37</ref> Zuloaga worked when gold was relatively abundant and his works make greater use of it than later Spanish damascene.<ref>Larra\u00f1aga, Ramiro \"Damascene as part of the Engraver's Art\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 38</ref> Although he made objects with a practical use, they are so delicate they would be damaged by ordinary use. Zuloaga's goal was beauty rather than practical utility.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}}\n\nMore than a hundred pieces of Spanish damascened metalwork, including 22 signed by Zuolaga, have been collected by the British-Iranian scholar and philanthropist [[Nasser Khalili|Nasser D. Khalili]], forming one of [[Khalili Collections|his eight collections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.khalilicollections.org/all-collections/spanish-damascene-metalwork/|title=Spanish Damascene Metalwork|last=|first=|date=|website=Khalili Collections|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Included in these are the Fonthill Casket, a {{convert|201|cm|in}} wide iron [[cassone]] with gold and silver damascening, decorated inside with white enamel with black ornamentation inside and out. Commissioned by the English collector [[Alfred Morrison]], it acquired its name from Fonthill manor, Morrison's family home. Zuloaga and his specialists took took two years to construct the casket,{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=71}} which was described in 1879 as \"a triumph of skilled workmanship\".{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}} Also commissioned by Morrison are a pair of [[amphora]]-shaped urns, {{convert|108|cm|in}} high, from 1878 whose style imitated the medieval [[Hispano-Moresque ware|Alhambra vases]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=83}} Covered in intricate Hispano-Arabic decoration, possibly drawn from contemporary engravings of a specific Alhambra vase, these were exhibited in Paris before delivery to Morrison.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=83}}\n\nA writing desk dated 1884\u20131885 has 44 drawers in a wooden case, each with enamelled floral patterns and a damascened metal button-pull.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=108}} Not a woodworker himself, Zuloaga would have subcontracted out the preparation of the wood and veneer.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=108}} A {{convert|47.3|cm|in}} high iron shrine dated 1880 recalls [[Gothic architecture]] in its overall shape, but the intricate damascened decoration is more suggestive of [[art nouveau]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=104}} It contains a cast silver figure of the Virgin and Child in a gothic style.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=104}} Other objects signed by Zuloaga include a [[revolver]],{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=102}} [[Decorative box|snuff boxes]] and caskets and containers of various dimensions.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|pp=90\u2013114}}\n\nAround 1872, Zuloaga's workshop was commissioned to make the monumental [[sarcophagus]] for [[Juan Prim, 1st Count of Reus|General Juan Prim]]. Work began in Eibar, but due to the [[Third Carlist War|civil war of 1873]] he moved his workshop across to the border to [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] in France where the work was completed. Prim's tomb now resides in the cemetary at [[Reus]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=58}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascene Metalwork cassone, Elbar.jpg|The Fonthill Casket: forged iron [[cassone]], 1871\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL104.jpg|Pair of iron urns, before 1878\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL105.jpg|Writing or document desk, 1884-1885\nFile:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL095.jpg|Iron shrine with [[Madonna (art)|virgin and child]], unknown date\n</gallery>\n\n== Personal life ==\nWith his first wife Luc\u00eda Zamora y Zabaleta, he had ten children, five of whom survived to adulthood, including [[Ignacio Zuloaga]] who would become a noted painter. After Lucia died, he married Francisca Gil y Lete.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Recognition and legacy ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork ZUL108.jpg|thumb|right|Iron table clock, circa 1880]]\nZuloaga died in Madrid at the age of 76 on 10 July 1910 and is interred in the cemetery at [[Canillejas]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} Several of his trainees continued as noted artists in their own right and EIbar continued as the centre of Spanish damascene production until the [[Spanish Civil War]].{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}}\n\nDuring his life, Zuolaga was awarded the Officer of the [[Legion of Honour|French Legion of Honor]], Knight Commander of the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic|Order of Isabel the Catholic]], Knight of the Great Cross of Charles III, Knight of the Great Cross of the Lion and Sword of Sweden, Cross of King Leopold of Belgium, Knight of the Portuguese Order of St. James, Grand Cross of Santiago of Portugal, and Knight of the Order of Maria Teresa of Austria.<ref name=\":0\" />{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}} He won many gold and silver medals at national and international exhibitions.{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=63}}\n\nThe critical reception of Zuloaga's art, and of Spanish damascened metalwork generally, has changed greatly over time. In 1872, the Keeper of Art Collections in the South Kensington Museum (later renamed the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]]) wrote that a vase decorated by Zuloaga \"will be regarded as one of the greatest Art productions of the century\".<ref name=\"blair\" /> An 1879 article said that the his works showed a patience and effort that \"take one into an era when the fine arts producer devoted himself solely to the cause of his ''m\u00e9tier'', apart from the commercial considerations of time, trouble and expense.\"{{sfn|Lavin|1997|p=57}} Early twentieth-century art critics took a more negative view of the Zuloaga family's works, but a new wave of interest and critical appreciation emerged in the last decades of that century.<ref name=\"blair\">[[Claude Blair|Blair, Claude]] \"Introduction\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 9</ref> Nasser Khalili, who writes that \"Spain [has] always led the West in its beauty and quality of its damascene production\", describes Zuloaga as \"the supreme damascener of [his] family\".<ref>[[Nasser Khalili|Khalili, Nasser D.]] \"Foreword\" in {{Harvnb|Lavin|1997}}, p. 8</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n[[File:Khalili Collection Spanish Damascened Metalwork zul109.jpg|thumb|right|Bronze gilt and enamelled casket, unknown date]]\nZuloaga exhibited his works at the 1855 [[Exposition Universelle (1855)|Paris International Exposition]] (where he was awarded a Medal of Honour)<ref name=\":0\" /> and at the Madrid Exhibition and the Brussels International Exhibition of 1856, then at the [[1862 International Exhibition|Great London Exposition]] of 1862.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMore recently, the following exhibitions have featured his work:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nasserdkhalili.com/the-eight-collections-2/|title=The Eight Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=nasserdkhalili.com|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Spanish Treasures from The Khalili Collection''\n\n* May 1997 \u2013 Jan 1998 [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], London, UK\n\n''El Arte y Tradici\u00f3n de los Zuloaga: Damasquinado Espa\u00f1ol de la Colecci\u00f3n Khalili''\n\n* May \u2013 Aug 2000 [[Museo de Bellas Artes de Bilbao|Museo de Bellas Artes]], Bilbao, Spain\n* Feb \u2013 Apr 2001 [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]], Granada, Spain\n* May \u2013 Sep 2001 [[Real Fundacion de Toledo]], Toledo, Spain\n\n''Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga: Meisterwerke in gold, silber und eisen damaszener\u2013schmiedekunst aus der Khalili-Sammlung''\n\n* Apr \u2013 Aug 2003 [[Roemer- und Pelizaeus-Museum Hildesheim|Roemer und Pelizaeus Museum]], Hildesheim, Germany\n\n''Metal Magic: Spanish Treasures from the Khalili Collection''\n\n* Nov 2011 \u2013 Apr 2012 [[Auberge de Provence]], Valletta, Malta\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Commons cat|Pl\u00e1cido Zuloaga}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Lavin|first=James D.|url=|title=The art and tradition of the Zuloagas : Spanish damascene from the Khalili Collection|date=1997|publisher=Khalili Family Trust in association with the Victoria and Albert Museum|others=|year=|isbn=1-874780-10-2|location=Oxford|pages=|oclc=37560664|ref=harv}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuloaga, Pl\u00e1cido}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:19th-century Spanish artists\u200e]]\n[[Category:People from Eibar]]\n[[Category:Spanish male artists]]\n[[Category:1910 deaths]]\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:19th-century male artists]]\n[[Category:Spanish metalsmiths]]\n", "name_user": "MartinPoulter", "label": "safe", "comment": "credit maker", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pl%C3%A1cido_Zuloaga"}
{"title_page": "T\u0129nh Gia District", "text_new": "{{Expand Vietnamese|date=March 2009|T\u0129nh Gia}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = T\u0129nh Gia District\n| settlement_type                 = [[Huy\u1ec7n|District]]\n| official_name                   = \n| other_name                      = \n| native_name                     = Huy\u1ec7n T\u0129nh Gia\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_skyline                   = \n| imagesize                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_flag                      = \n| flag_size                       = \n| image_seal                      = \n| seal_size                       = \n| image_shield                    = \n| shield_size                     = \n| image_blank_emblem              = \n| blank_emblem_size               = \n| image_map                       = \n| mapsize                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| image_map1                      = \n| mapsize1                        = \n| map_caption1                    = \n| pushpin_map                     = \n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Regions of Vietnam|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[North Central Coast]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Provinces of Vietnam|Province]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Thanh H\u00f3a Province|Thanh H\u00f3a]]\n| seat_type                       = Capital\n| seat                            = T\u0129nh Gia\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = \n| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n| leader_name1                    = \n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = \n| area_magni