archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref> The song written by veteran poet [[Syed Shamsul Haque]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channelionline.com/%e0%a6%b8%e0%a7%88%e0%a7%9f%e0%a6%a6-%e0%a6%b6%e0%a6%be%e0%a6%ae%e0%a6%b8%e0%a7%81%e0%a6%b2-%e0%a6%b9%e0%a6%95%e0%a7%87%e0%a6%b0-%e0%a6%a6%e0%a7%8d%e0%a6%ac%e0%a6%bf%e0%a6%a4%e0%a7%80%e0%a7%9f/|title=\u09b8\u09c8\u09af\u09bc\u09a6 \u09b6\u09be\u09ae\u09b8\u09c1\u09b2 \u09b9\u0995\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a6\u09cd\u09ac\u09bf\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u09ae\u09c3\u09a4\u09cd\u09af\u09c1\u09ac\u09be\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09bf\u0995\u09c0|last=|first=|date=2018-09-27|website=Channel I Online|language=bn|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref> composed by [[Alam Khan (composer)|Alam Khan]] and sung by [[Andrew Kishore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banglatribune.com/others/news/143883|title=\u2018\u09b9\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7, \u09b0\u0999\u09bf\u09a8 \u09ab\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b8\u2019|last=|first=|date=2016-09-16|website=[[Bangla Tribune]]|language=bn|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kalerkantho.com/online/entertainment/2016/09/27/409971|title='\u09b9\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7 \u09b0\u0999\u09bf\u09a8 \u09ab\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b8 \u09a6\u09ae \u09ab\u09c1\u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09b2\u09c7\u0987 \u09a0\u09c1\u09b8'|last=|first=|date=2016-09-27|website=Kalerkantho|language=bn|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref> [[Anwar Hossain (actor)|Anwar Hossain]] and [[Prabir Mitra]] performed in the song.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://bangla.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/article1219396.bdnews|title=\u2018\u09a6\u09ae \u09ab\u09c1\u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09b2\u09c7 \u09a0\u09c1\u09b8\u2019|last=|first=|date=2016-09-27|website=bangla.bdnews24.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.somoynews.tv/pages/details/62110|title=\u09b9\u09be\u09af\u09bc\u09b0\u09c7 \u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b7 \u09b0\u0999\u09cd\u0997\u09bf\u09a8 \u09ab\u09be\u09a8\u09c1\u09b8 \u09a6\u09ae \u09ab\u09c1\u09b0\u09be\u0987\u09b2\u09c7 \u09a0\u09c1\u09b8|last=|first=|date=2016-09-27|website=somoynews.tv|language=bn|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/entertainment/article/720973|title=\u0986\u09ae\u09bf \u0995\u0996\u09a8\u09cb \u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u09b2\u09bf\u0996\u09a4\u09c7 \u099a\u09be\u0987\u09a8\u09bf|last=|first=|date=2015-12-24|website=[[Prothom Alo]]|language=bn|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nThe song was recorded at the Shruti Studio in [[Magbazar]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.prothomalo.com/entertainment/article/667474/%E0%A6%86%E0%A6%B2%E0%A6%AE-%E0%A6%96%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%97%E0%A6%BE%E0%A6%A8-%E0%A6%93-%E0%A6%97%E0%A6%B2%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%AA|title=\u0986\u09b2\u09ae \u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u0993 \u0997\u09b2\u09cd\u09aa|website=Prothom Alo|language=bn|access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe song was released on 1982 as the part of soundtrack album of the film. After Thirty-six years of the film release, the song was revealed under the banner of [[G-Series]] on there official [[YouTube]] channel on April 5, 2018.<ref>{{Citation|title=Old Movie Songs {{!}} Haire Manush Rongin Fanush {{!}} by Andrew Kishore {{!}} Boro Valo Lok Chilo|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_vZxuod-Db8|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Awards\n!Category\n!Nominated\n!Result\n!Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[7th Bangladesh National Film Awards|1982]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[National Film Awards (Bangladesh)|National Film Awards]]\n|[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Music Director|Best Music Director]]\n|[[Alam Khan (composer)|Alam Khan]]\n|{{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fdc.gov.bd/site/page/f3bb17fe-d9ad-4b61-bd8a-5824262691ad/%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AF%E0%A7%AD%E0%A7%AB-%E0%A7%A8%E0%A7%A6%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%A8|title=\u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09c0\u09af\u09bc \u099a\u09b2\u099a\u09cd\u099a\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0 \u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09b8\u09cd\u0995\u09be\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09be\u09aa\u09cd\u09a4\u09a6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a8\u09be\u09ae\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a4\u09be\u09b2\u09bf\u0995\u09be (\u09e7\u09ef\u09ed\u09eb-\u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09e8)|last=|first=|date=|website=fdc.gov.bd|language=bn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223211753/http://www.fdc.gov.bd/site/page/f3bb17fe-d9ad-4b61-bd8a-5824262691ad/%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%AF%E0%A7%AD%E0%A7%AB-%E0%A7%A8%E0%A7%A6%E0%A7%A7%E0%A7%A8|archive-date=2 December 2018|access-date=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bangladesh National Film Award for Best Male Playback Singer|Best Male Playback Singer]]\n|[[Andrew Kishore]]\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|_vZxuod-Db8|Hayre Manush Rangin Phanush|suffix='}}\n* [http://www.banglatribune.com/others/news/143883 Hayre Manush Rangin Phanush song lyrics] on Bangla Tribune (in Bengali)\n\n[[Category:Bangladeshi film songs]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language songs]]\n[[Category:1982 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:Bengali film songs]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Film Awards (Bangladesh)]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toG series(link changed toG-Series (record label)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hayre_Manush_Rangin_Phanush"}
{"title_page": "Floyd Robinson (singer)", "text_new": "'''Floyd Eugene Robinson''' (August 10, 1932 \u2013 May 28, 2016)<ref name= TheTennessean >{{cite news|url= http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tennessean/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=180194354 |title= Floyd Eugene Robinson |date= June 3, 2016|newspaper=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=MusicRow>{{cite web|url= http://www.musicrow.com/2016/06/lifenotes-popcountry-stylist-floyd-robinson-passes/ |title=LifeNotes: Pop/Country Stylist Floyd Robinson Passes |website= Musicrow.com |date= June 3, 2016 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> was an American [[country music|country]] singer, born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], who was briefly successful in the late 1950s.\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nRobinson's music was similar stylistically to that of [[John D. Loudermilk]], and Robinson, like Loudermilk, worked as a [[songwriter]]. Among his songwriting contributions was \"The Little Space Girl\", a hit for his cousin, [[Jesse Lee Turner]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1088230|pure_url=yes}} Review of ''Makin' Love], [[AllMusic]]</ref> Robinson recorded for [[King Records (USA)|King Records]] (1954), [[RCA Victor]], [[Dot Records|Dot]], [[Jamie Records|Jamie]], and [[Groove Records|Groove]] over the course of his career, and released a full-length [[album]] on RCA. He scored one hit single in the [[United States|US]], \"[[Makin' Love (Floyd Robinson song)|Makin' Love]]\", which reached No.&nbsp;27 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Black Singles]] [[record chart|chart]], and No.&nbsp;20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1959. The track reached No.&nbsp;9 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] the same year.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book|first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= British Hit Singles & Albums| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 465}}</ref>\n\nIn the US, \"Makin' Love\" was controversial because of its suggestive sexual content and many radio stations pulled it from the airwaves after only a few weeks.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nGolden Sandy Records released a [[compilation album]] of Robinson's recorded output, including his entire 1959 full-length, on [[Compact disc|CD]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/floyd-robinson-mn0000160592|title=Floyd Robinson : Discography|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nFrom approximately 1973 to 1977, Robinson recorded and released religious-themed children's albums, as characters Charlie the Hamster, Ricky the Cricket, and Woody Woodchuck.\n\nIn the 1990s Robinson self-published two books, the instruction manual ''Guitar Playing Made Easy'' (1992), and the novel ''The Guitar'' (1994). He owned a used car dealership, but remained active in the [[music industry]].<ref name=\"Discoogle\">[http://www.123people.co.uk/ext/frm?ti=person%20finder&search_term=floyd%20robinson&search_country=GB&st=person%20finder&target_url=http%3A%2F%2Flrd.yahooapis.com%2F_ylc%3DX3oDMTVnN2ltdWNtBF9TAzIwMjMxNTI3MDIEYXBwaWQDc1k3Wlo2clYzNEhSZm5ZdGVmcmkzRUx4VG5makpERG5QOWVKV1NGSkJHcTJ1V1dFa0xVdm5IYnNBeUNyVkd5Y2REVElUX2tlBGNsaWVudANib3NzBHNlcnZpY2UDQk9TUwRzbGsDdGl0bGUEc3JjcHZpZANhbVdBcFdLSWNycGEyMGNyb3VZTjZjT1hXODV4dDBybmtNa0FDdEdw%2FSIG%3D11i7p72v3%2F**http%253A%2F%2Fwww.discoogle.com%2Fwiki%2FRobinson%2C_Floyd&section=biography&wrt_id=107] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nRobinson died on May 28, 2016 in [[Hendersonville, Tennessee]] after a long illness, at age 83.<ref name= MusicRow/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Floyd}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:King Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Floyd Eugene Robinson''' (August 10, 1932 \u2013 May 28, 2016)<ref name= TheTennessean >{{cite news|url= http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tennessean/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=180194354 |title= Floyd Eugene Robinson |date= June 3, 2016|newspaper=[[The Tennessean]] |accessdate=April 8, 2015}}</ref><ref name=MusicRow>{{cite web|url= http://www.musicrow.com/2016/06/lifenotes-popcountry-stylist-floyd-robinson-passes/ |title=LifeNotes: Pop/Country Stylist Floyd Robinson Passes |website= Musicrow.com |date= June 3, 2016 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> was an American [[country music|country]] singer, born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], who was briefly successful in the late 1950s.\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nRobinson's music was similar stylistically to that of [[John D. Loudermilk]], and Robinson, like Loudermilk, worked as a [[songwriter]]. Among his songwriting contributions was \"The Little Space Girl\", a hit for his cousin, [[Jesse Lee Turner]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1088230|pure_url=yes}} Review of ''Makin' Love], [[AllMusic]]</ref> Robinson recorded for [[King Records (USA)|King Records]] (1954), [[RCA Victor]], [[Dot Records|Dot]], [[Jamie Records|Jamie]], and [[Groove Records|Groove]] over the course of his career, and released a full-length [[album]] on RCA. He scored one hit single in the [[United States|US]], \"[[Makin' Love (Floyd Robinson song)|Makin' Love]]\", which reached No.&nbsp;27 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Black Singles]] [[record chart|chart]], and No.&nbsp;20 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] in 1959. The track reached No.&nbsp;9 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] the same year.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book|first= David| last= Roberts| year= 2006| title= British Hit Singles & Albums| edition= 19th| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London| isbn= 1-904994-10-5| page= 465}}</ref>\n\nIn the US, \"Makin' Love\" was controversial because of its suggestive sexual content and many radio stations pulled it from the airwaves after only a few weeks.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nGolden Sandy Records released a [[compilation album]] of Robinson's recorded output, including his entire 1959 full-length, on [[Compact disc|CD]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/floyd-robinson-mn0000160592|title=Floyd Robinson : Discography|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nFrom approximately 1973 to 1977, Robinson recorded and released religious-themed children's albums, as characters Charlie the Hamster, Ricky the Cricket, and Woody Woodchuck.\n\nIn the 1990s Robinson self-published two books, the instruction manual ''Guitar Playing Made Easy'' (1992), and the novel ''The Guitar'' (1994). He owned a used car dealership, but remained active in the [[music industry]].<ref name=\"Discoogle\">[http://www.123people.co.uk/ext/frm?ti=person%20finder&search_term=floyd%20robinson&search_country=GB&st=person%20finder&target_url=http%3A%2F%2Flrd.yahooapis.com%2F_ylc%3DX3oDMTVnN2ltdWNtBF9TAzIwMjMxNTI3MDIEYXBwaWQDc1k3Wlo2clYzNEhSZm5ZdGVmcmkzRUx4VG5makpERG5QOWVKV1NGSkJHcTJ1V1dFa0xVdm5IYnNBeUNyVkd5Y2REVElUX2tlBGNsaWVudANib3NzBHNlcnZpY2UDQk9TUwRzbGsDdGl0bGUEc3JjcHZpZANhbVdBcFdLSWNycGEyMGNyb3VZTjZjT1hXODV4dDBybmtNa0FDdEdw%2FSIG%3D11i7p72v3%2F**http%253A%2F%2Fwww.discoogle.com%2Fwiki%2FRobinson%2C_Floyd&section=biography&wrt_id=107] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\nRobinson died on May 28, 2016 in [[Hendersonville, Tennessee]] after a long illness, at age 83.<ref name= MusicRow/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robinson, Floyd}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:King Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floyd_Robinson_(singer)"}
